  "religion": "Curie was probably an agnostic, but certainly non-religious in a heavily religious society.",
  "politicalViews": "Curie was a revolutionary, a feminist and maybe a libertarian.",
  "author": "Tom Kershaw",
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "text": "Marie Curie, born Maria Sklodowska, was born and raised in Warsaw, Poland. Due to her work with radioactive materials, Curie contracted leukemia and died of pernicious anemia in 1934."
    },
    {
      "type": "break"
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "sourceUrl": "http://www.adherents.com/people/pc/Marie_Curie.html",
      "sourceTitle": "The religion of Marie Curie, physicist",
      "text": "Curie, being Polish and living most of her life in France, was surrounded by Catholicism and her mother was an active Catholic. Her father, who was a physics professor in Warsaw, is cited as having been a \"freethinker,\""
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "text": "which is code for atheist."
    },
    {
      "type": "break"
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "sourceUrl": "http://www.celebatheists.com/wiki/Marie_Curie",
      "sourceTitle": "Marie Curie",
      "text": "Curie herself was not religious, and is often considered an atheist,"
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "text": "but it seems more likely given her scientific worldview that she was more of an agnostic. She said:"
    },
    {
      "type": "break"
    },
    {
      "type": "quote",
      "sourceUrl": "http://www.brainyquote.com/quotes/authors/m/marie_curie.html",
      "sourceTitle": "Marie Curie Quotes",
      "text": "Nothing in life is to be feared, it is only to be understood. Now is the time to understand more, so that we may fear less."
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "text": "Writing of her marriage to Pierre Curie (in a civil, non-religious ceremony), she revealed the secular nature of both Pierre and herself:"
    },
    {
      "type": "break"
    },
    {
      "type": "quote",
      "sourceUrl": "http://www.adherents.com/people/pc/Marie_Curie.html",
      "sourceTitle": "The religion of Marie Curie, physicist",
      "text": "Pierre belonged to no religion and I did not practice any."
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "text": "This may all seem rather vague, but when considering the highly religious environment of Europe during the 19th Century, for Curie to be so nonchalant about religion amounts to a bold statement against the social conventions of her time."
    },
    {
      "type": "break"
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "Science, women and politics"
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "sourceUrl": "http://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1903/marie-curie-bio.html",
      "sourceTitle": "Marie Curie – Biography",
      "text": "Curie was a bit of a revolutionary. During her youth in Warsaw, she participated in a student's revolutionary organization protesting Russian occupation of that part of Poland, and ultimately was forced to flee to Krakow (then a part of the Austrian Empire) to escape a potential backlash."
    },
    {
      "type": "break"
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "sourceUrl": "http://womenshistory.about.com/od/mariecurie/p/marie_curie.htm",
      "sourceTitle": "Marie Curie – Women's History.",
      "text": "Curie was fiercely loyal to France in her later years and during World War I, she drove ambulances (that she had equipped with x-ray equipment for the French government) to the front lines of the war."
    },
    {
      "type": "break"
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "sourceUrl": "http://womenshistory.about.com/od/mariecurie/p/marie_curie.htm",
      "sourceTitle": "Marie Curie – Women's History.",
      "text": "However, France was not always kind to her, and in her battles with the patriarchal scientific community there, Curie became a champion of early feminism. She was the first woman to get a Ph.D in research science in Europe, the first woman professor at the Sorbonne, the first woman to win a Nobel Prize and the first person ever to win two Nobel Prizes in different scientific disciplines."
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "text": "She certainly proved for many women that they could run with the scientific big dogs."
    },
    {
      "type": "break"
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "text": "Despite her brilliance, Curie was denied a place in the French Academy of Sciences, with the stated reason being:"
    },
    {
      "type": "break"
    },
    {
      "type": "quote",
      "sourceUrl": "http://womenshistory.about.com/od/mariecurie/p/marie_curie.htm",
      "sourceTitle": "Marie Curie – Women's History.",
      "text": "Women cannot be part of the Institute of France."
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "sourceUrl": "http://womenshistory.about.com/od/mariecurie/p/marie_curie.htm",
      "sourceTitle": "Marie Curie – Women's History.",
      "text": "As a result, she wouldn't allow the Academy to publish her work for the next ten years."
    },
    {
      "type": "break"
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "sourceUrl": "http://womenshistory.about.com/od/mariecurie/p/marie_curie.htm",
      "sourceTitle": "Marie Curie – Women's History.",
      "text": "Also, and I'm tempted to call Curie a libertarian (by modern standards of course), after her husband died, leaving her to care for their two children alone, Curie refused state welfare assistance."
    },
    {
      "type": "sentence",
      "text": "As to why she did that, details are a bit sparse. If any of you commenters would like to weigh in on this, I'd love to hear your thoughts."
    },
    {
      "type": "break"
    }
  ],
